　　But once we rip off the band-aid, tuck our smartphones in our pockets and look up, it doesn’t<mark>12</mark>so bad. In one 2011 experiment, behavioral scientists Nicholas Epley and Juliana Schroeder asked commuters to do the unthinkable: Start a<mark>13</mark>. They had Chicago train commuters talk to their fellow <mark>14</mark>. “When Dr. Epley and Ms. Schroeder asked other people in the same train station to <mark>15</mark> how they would feel after talking to a stranger, the commuters thought their <mark>16</mark> would be more pleasant if they sat on their own,” the New York Times summarizes. Though the participants didn’t expect a positive experience, after they<mark>17</mark>with the experiment, “not a single person reported having been embarrassed.”
